We had to stop using our canrange which was equipped in our intake to detect pieces. It was confident when a piece was in there, and we had it coded right for range calibration. However, if a piece wasnt in there, it would “detect” a piece like every 2 seconds, meaning for autonomous we couldnt use it to detect if it picked something up. We tested it, and it only happened when the lights in the room were on. Could this be some weird trick of light? and how could we fix it

First, make sure you set up your ProximityThreshold config based on the distance you measured when you did have a game piece. You can also adjust the ProximityHysteresis to prevent bouncing between the detected/undetected states when an object is at the edge of the detection threshold.

With all that said, if you’re still seeing false positives in high lighting, then I would suspect that the MinSignalStrengthForValidMeasurement config may be too low. Since CANrange is a Time of Flight sensor, it uses light to determine distance, and signal strength is a measurement of the strength of the return signal. With higher ambient lighting, the ambient signal strength will be higher, which may be crossing the default threshold. So I would check the signal strength when the object should be detected, reduce that a bit to give yourself some wiggle room, and adjust the config accordingly.

Edit: Also note that for proximity detect, as was mentioned previously by @Jimmyy, you should use getIsDetected() and not a pure distance check.
